\Section[Population]
\SubSection[Demographics]
Nauru had 10,670 residents as of July 2018.\Cite("ref4")\Cite("ref5") The population was previously larger, but in 2006 1,500 people left the island during a repatriation of immigrant workers from Kiribati and Tuvalu. The repatriation was motivated by significant layoffs in phosphate mining.\Cite("ref103")
\\
Nauru is one of the most Westernized countries in the South Pacific.\Cite("ref122")
\\
\SubSection[Ethnic groups]
Fifty-eight percent of people in Nauru are ethnically Nauruan, 26 percent are other Pacific Islander, 8 percent are European, and 8 percent are Han Chinese.\Cite("ref2")
\\
\SubSection[Languages]
The official language of Nauru is Nauruan,\Cite("ref1") a distinct Micronesian language, which is spoken by 96 per cent of ethnic Nauruans at home.\Cite("ref103") English is widely spoken and is the language of government and commerce, as Nauruan is not used outside the country.\Cite("ref2")\Cite("ref3")
\\
\SubSection[Religion]
The main religion practised on the island is Christianity (the main denominations are Nauru Congregational Church 35.71%, Roman Catholic 32.96%, Assemblies of God 12.98%, and Baptist 1.48%).\Cite("ref3") The Constitution provides for freedom of religion. The government has restricted the religious practices of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints and the Jehovah's Witnesses, most of whom are foreign workers employed by the government-owned Nauru Phosphate Corporation.\Cite("ref123") The Catholics are pastorally served by the Roman Catholic Diocese of Tarawa and Nauru, with see at Tarawa in Kiribati.
\\\\
\Section[Culture]
Angam Day, held on 26 October, celebrates the recovery of the Nauruan population after the two World Wars and the 1920 influenza epidemic.\Cite("ref124") The displacement of the indigenous culture by colonial and contemporary Western influences is significant.\Cite("ref125") Few of the old customs have been preserved, but some forms of traditional music, arts and crafts, and fishing are still practised.\Cite("ref126")
\\
\SubSection[Media]
There are no daily news publications on Nauru, although there is one fortnightly publication, Mwinen Ko. There is a state-owned television station, Nauru Television (NTV), which broadcasts programs from New Zealand and Australia, and a state-owned non-commercial radio station, Radio Nauru, which carries programs from Radio Australia and the BBC.\Cite("ref127")
\\
\SubSection[Sport]
Australian rules football is the most popular sport in Nauru—it and weightlifting are considered the country's national sports. There is an Australian rules football league with eight teams.\Cite("ref128") Other sports popular in Nauru include volleyball, netball, fishing, weightlifting and tennis. Many weightlifters on the islands have skilfully secured competitions and defeated athletes of far bigger nations. Nauru participates in the Commonwealth Games and has participated in the Summer Olympic Games in weightlifting and judo.\Cite("ref129")
\\
Nauru's national basketball team competed at the 1969 Pacific Games, where it defeated the Solomon Islands and Fiji.
\\
The Nauru national rugby sevens team made its international debut at the 2015 Pacific Games.\Cite("ref130")
\\
Nauru competed in the 2015 Oceania Sevens Championship in New Zealand.
\\
\SubSection[Holidays]
Independence Day is celebrated on 31 January.\Cite("ref131")
\\\\
\Section[Public Services]
\SubSection[Education]
Literacy on Nauru is 96 percent. Education is compulsory for children from six to sixteen years old, and two more non-compulsory years are offered (years 11 and 12).\Cite("ref132") The island has three primary schools and two secondary schools, the latter being Nauru College and Nauru Secondary School.\Cite("ref133") There is a campus of the University of the South Pacific on Nauru. Before this campus was built in 1987, students would study either by distance or abroad.\Cite("ref134") Since 2011, the University of New England, Australia has established a presence on the island with around 30 Nauruan teachers studying for an associate degree in education. These students will continue onto the degree to complete their studies.\Cite("ref135") This project is led by Associate Professor Pep Serow and funded by the Australian Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade.
\\
The previous community public library was destroyed in a fire. As of 1999 a new one had not yet been built, and no bookmobile services are available as of that year. Sites with libraries include the University of the South Pacific campus, Nauru Secondary, Kayser College, and Aiwo Primary.\Cite("ref136") The Nauru Community Library is in the new University of the South Pacific Nauru Campus building, which was officially opened in May 2018.
\\
\SubSection[Health]
Life expectancy on Nauru in 2009 was 60.6 years for males and 68.0 years for females.\Cite("ref138")
\\
By measure of mean body mass index (BMI), Nauruans are the most overweight people in the world;\Cite("ref137") 97 per cent of men and 93 per cent of women are overweight or obese.\Cite("ref137") In 2012, the obesity rate was 71.7 per cent.\Cite("ref139") Obesity on the Pacific islands is common.
\\
Nauru has the world's highest level of type 2 diabetes, with more than 40 per cent of the population affected.\Cite("ref140") Other significant dietary-related problems on Nauru include kidney disease and heart disease.\Cite("ref138")
